VALUES
(44, 7, 33, 2, 3, 5, 5, 'put off thy shoes from thy feet', 'Connection of Holy Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''put off thy shoes from thy feet'' in the context of holy ground. This connection highlights the sacredness of the location where God speaks.', 'quotation', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 33, 6, 5, 15, 15, 'for the place where thou standest is holy', 'Holy Ground Command', 'Both passages emphasize the command to remove shoes in the presence of holy ground. This connection highlights the sacredness of the locations where God reveals Himself.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 33, 21, 5, 1, 1, 'holy ground', 'Holiness and Reverence', 'This connection highlights the theme of holiness in approaching God. Both passages emphasize the need for reverence, as seen in ''holy ground'' and ''keep thy foot.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 33, 61, 1, 18, 18, 'holy ground', 'Holy Ground and Holy Mount', 'This connection highlights the concept of holiness in both passages. Acts 7:33 refers to a place as ''holy ground,'' while 2 Peter 1:18 mentions a ''holy mount,'' emphasizing the sacredness of these locations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 2, 3, 7, 10, 'I have seen, I have seen', 'Divine Deliverance of Israel', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of Israel''s affliction and His intention to deliver them from Egypt. The repetition of phrases like ''I have seen'' and ''I am come down to deliver them'' underscores this connection.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 2, 4, 31, 31, NULL, 'Divine Response to Affliction', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s awareness and response to the affliction of His people. Both passages emphasize God''s observation of suffering and His intention to deliver, leading to the people''s worship in response to His intervention.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 16, 9, 9, 9, 'affliction of my people which is in Egypt', 'Affliction and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of the affliction of His people in Egypt and His response to their cries for help. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s concern and action in delivering His people from suffering.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 19, 106, 44, 44, 'affliction of my people which is in Egypt', 'Affliction and Divine Response', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of affliction and His response to the cries of His people. Acts 7:34 speaks of God seeing the affliction and hearing the groaning, while Psalms 106:44 highlights His regard for their affliction when He hears their cry.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 43, 6, 38, 38, NULL, 'Divine Mission and Delivery', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in human affairs. Both passages emphasize the act of coming down to fulfill a mission: God to deliver His people from Egypt and Jesus to accomplish the will of the Father.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 23, 63, 8, 9, 'affliction of my people which is in Egypt', 'Affliction and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s awareness of affliction and His role in delivering His people. Acts 7:34 speaks of God''s response to the groaning of His people, while Isaiah 63:8-9 highlights His presence and salvation in their affliction.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 34, 28, 12, 13, 13, 'I have seen the affliction of my people', 'Deliverance through Prophetic Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance, as both passages refer to God''s action in rescuing His people from Egypt. Acts 7:34 emphasizes God''s call to Moses for deliverance, while Hosea 12:13 attributes Israel''s exodus and preservation to a prophet.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 19, 118, 22, 23, 'whom they refused', 'Rejection and Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. Moses is initially refused as a ruler, paralleling the stone rejected by builders that becomes central to God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 42, 19, 14, 14, 'Who made thee a ruler', 'Rejection of Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of divinely appointed leaders. In both passages, the citizens and the people refuse to accept the authority of those chosen by God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 4, 20, 16, 16, 'the same did God send to be a ruler and a deliverer', 'Moses as Deliverer', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in sending an angel to deliver His people. Acts 7:35 refers to Moses as a ruler and deliverer, while Numbers 20:16 mentions an angel sent to bring the Israelites out of Egypt.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 19, 75, 7, 7, NULL, 'Divine Authority in Leadership', 'This connection highlights God''s role in establishing leaders. Both passages emphasize that God appoints rulers and judges according to His will.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 2, 14, 19, 19, 'by the hand of the angel', 'Divine Guidance Through Angels', 'This connection highlights the role of the angel in guiding God''s people. In Acts, Moses is sent by God through the angel, while in Exodus, the angel of God leads the Israelites.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 2, 23, 20, 23, 'the same did God send to be a ruler', 'Moses and the Angel Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of the angel as a divine messenger. Both passages emphasize God''s guidance through the angel, with Moses being appointed as a ruler and deliverer.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 35, 9, 8, 7, 8, 'Who made thee a ruler and a judge?', 'Rejection of God''s Chosen Leaders', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of God''s appointed leaders. In both passages, the people reject Moses and Samuel, indicating a pattern of forsaking divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 2, 12, 41, 41, NULL, 'Exodus and Wilderness Journey', 'This connection highlights the theme of deliverance from Egypt, as both passages describe the Israelites'' exodus. Acts 7:36 references the signs and wonders that preceded their departure, while Exodus 12:41 marks the moment they left Egypt.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 2, 14, 21, 21, 'wonders and signs in the land of Egypt', 'Moses and the Red Sea', 'This connection highlights the miraculous events associated with Moses, specifically the division of the sea. Both passages emphasize the signs and wonders performed by God through Moses during the Exodus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 19, 78, 12, 33, 'wonders and signs in the land of Egypt', 'Miraculous Signs and Provision', 'Both passages emphasize God''s miraculous acts during the Exodus, including dividing the sea and providing sustenance in the wilderness. They highlight the theme of divine intervention and the people''s response to God''s wonders.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 4, 11, 1, 35, NULL, 'Complaints and Divine Response', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s complaints and God''s response. In Acts, the focus is on the signs and wonders during the Exodus, while Numbers details the people''s dissatisfaction with manna and God''s provision of quail, highlighting a recurring theme of discontent and divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 4, 14, 1, 45, NULL, 'Signs and Miracles in Wilderness', 'Both passages emphasize the signs and wonders shown by the Lord during the Israelites'' journey. Acts 7:36 mentions these wonders in Egypt and the wilderness, while Numbers 14:22 refers to the miracles seen by the people, highlighting their lack of faith despite witnessing God''s power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 5, 2, 25, 37, 'wonders and signs', 'Divine Deliverance and Conquest', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in delivering Israel from their enemies. Acts 7:36 mentions the wonders and signs during the Exodus, while Deuteronomy 2:25-37 describes God''s deliverance of Sihon into Israel''s hands.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 36, 5, 4, 33, 37, 'wonders and signs', 'Signs and Wonders Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God demonstrating his power through signs and wonders. Acts 7:36 mentions ''wonders and signs'' performed in Egypt, while Deuteronomy 4:33-37 recounts similar acts that reveal God''s might and purpose in delivering Israel from Egypt.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 5, 18, 15, 19, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Moses and the Prophet Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of a prophet raised up by God from among the people, specifically stating he will be ''like unto me.'' This connection highlights the continuity of prophetic leadership from Moses to the anticipated future prophet.', 'prophecy', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 44, 3, 22, 23, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up unto you of your brethren, like unto me; him shall ye hear.', 'Connection of Moses and the Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize Moses'' prophecy about a prophet like him. They highlight the importance of listening to this prophet, indicating a direct link between Moses and the future figure.', 'quotation', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 43, 18, 37, 37, 'him shall ye hear', 'Connection of Prophetic Voice', 'This connection highlights the theme of prophetic authority. In Acts, Moses speaks of a prophet to be heard, while in John, Jesus emphasizes that those who are of the truth hear his voice.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 40, 17, 3, 5, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Moses and the Prophet Connection', 'This connection highlights the reference to Moses as a prophet in Acts 7:37, which parallels the appearance of Moses in Matthew 17:3-5. Both passages emphasize the importance of listening to God''s chosen messenger, as seen in the command to ''hear ye him.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 44, 7, 38, 38, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Connection Between Moses and Prophecy', 'This connection highlights Moses as a prophet and his role in delivering God''s message. Both passages emphasize the significance of Moses in the wilderness and the prophetic expectation of a future leader.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
